               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1322" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1322" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1322" type="surname" value="SEAGER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1322" type="given" value="EBENEZER"></interp>EBENEZER SEAGER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of John Richard Nicholl Clerk, the prisoner was a bricklayer in his employ—the top course of a wan was</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184904090223"></xptr>
               <p>pulled down, and instead of replacing the bricks be took them away—I found him with the truck loaded with them—I stopped him and told him to take them back—he had three men with him, whom he had employed to do a job with these bricks—he said, "There were enough of them to throw me into the ditch"—I followed the bricks and got an officer and took them; this is one of them, they are all marked "W. G."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1323" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1323" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1323" type="surname" value="MANSFIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1323" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL MANSFIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I saw the prisoner take the bricks off the house, bring them down the ladder, and take them away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> He plays at pitch and toss all day on Sunday; he has been a fatherless child; I have brought him up; he has done but six months' work these eighteen years. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> When I was ill he turned me out because I could not work; my mother brought me up, not him—my mother lives with him—I cannot read.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1324" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1324" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1324" type="surname" value="BULLPIT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1324" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BULLPIT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am employed by Mr. Seager to repair these houses—I was on one time and the prisoner another—I found the party wall stripped—these bricks belonged to that wall.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1325" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1325" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1325" type="surname" value="CHILD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1325" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS CHILD</persName>
                  </hi>. I lived with the prisoner; I know he had no bricks belonging to him; he had none on his own premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1326" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1326" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1326" type="surname" value="RICHARDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1326" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS RICHARDS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman M</hi> 44). These are the bricks, they are all marked "<hi rend="italic">W.</hi> G."—the prisoner said they were his own—he had taken them best part of a mile and was working them into a chimney.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I have been a master bricklayer nine years—I have had from ten to twelve thousand bricks—it is all from prejudice.</p>
